the Iberian Peninsula (Castilian, Catalan, Portuguese and Basque), between Spanish or Portuguese and another language (such as English), and between different varieties from Europe and other continents. The volume thus unites views from two fields that rarely interact: contact linguistics and dialectology. It discusses the mechanisms and consequences of language contact within the Ibero-Romance world, a geographical space characterised by a high rate of multilingual speakers and settings. The contributions deal with various combinations of convergence and divergence, for example between different varieties of the same language, language stability despite contact, as well as less studied aspects, such as the relation between language contact and second language acquisition, the linguistic landscape perspective of language contact, and divergence in linguistic identity construction.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aHistorical linguistics. 0aLanguages in contact. 0aRomance languageszIberian PeninsulaxHistory. 0aRomance languages. 4aIberoromanisch / Sprachvariante. 4aSprachkontakt. 4aSprachvariation. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Spanish.2bisacsh  aDiatopic Variation.  aIbero-Romance.  aLanguage Contact.1 aAfonso, Susana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergareche, Bruno Camus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouzouita, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouzouita, Miriam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEnghels, Renata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnghels, Renata, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGras, Pedro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/